   <abstract><p>Abstract copyright UK Data Service and data collection copyright owner.</p>The <i>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)</i> produces annual, quarterly and monthly data for around 3,800 main economic indicators (MEI). The variables cover national accounts, industrial production, employment, prices, business trends and trade for the member countries of the OECD and 6 non-member countries. The dataset also includes the OECD's leading indicators (key variables that signal changes in the business cycle).<br> <br> The OECD defines each variable separately for each country. Nevertheless, the data are considered sufficiently similar to enable comparisons between countries, especially for relative values and rates of change.<br> <br> These data were first provided by the UK Data Service in January 2003. The UK Data Service web site includes further information on its <i>OECD MEI</i> holdings, including a <a href="http://ukdataservice.ac.uk/use-data/guides/dataset/economic-indicators.aspx" title="OECD Main Economic Indicators Databank dataset user guide">dataset user guide</a> and details of <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.5257/oecd/mei/2011-09" title="OECD Main Economic Indicators Databank latest database updates">latest database updates</a>.<br> <br> <b>Citation:</b> The bibliographic citation for the database is: Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (<i>{YYYY}</i>): Main Economic Indicators (<i>{Ed. YYYY-MM}</i>). Mimas, University of Manchester. DOI: <i>{edition specific doi - e.g. <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.5257/oecd/mei/2011-09">http://dx.doi.org/10.5257/oecd/mei/2011-09</a>}</i>.<br> <br> <b>Alternative DOIs:</b> <a href="http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/economics/data/main-economic-indicators_mei-data-en" title="10.1787/mei-data-en">10.1787/mei-data-en</a> (to access via OECD.Stat subscription).<br> <br> </abstract>       <abstract><B>Main Topics</B>:<br>The topics listed below correspond to the first OECD subject level:<ul><li>leading indicators (indicators that run 6-12 months ahead of GNP cycle)</li><li>national accounts</li><li>national income</li><li>production</li><li>business tendency surveys</li><li>consumer surveys</li><li>manufacturing</li><li>construction</li><li>domestic demand</li><li>employment</li><li>unemployment</li><li>other labour market indicators</li><li>labour compensation</li><li>producer prices</li><li>consumer price index</li><li>other prices</li><li>monetary aggregates and their components </li><li>domestic credit and debt</li><li>interest rates</li><li>security issues </li><li>share prices</li><li>currency conversions</li><li>external finance</li><li>foreign trade</li><li>balance of payments</li><li>capital and financial accounts</li><li>financial accounts</li><li>net errors and omissions</li><li>world trade</li></ul><br> </abstract>       <sumDscr>         <timePrd>The <i>OECD MEI</i> are released monthly and run from January 1960 to the current month.</timePrd>         <nation>Multi-nation</nation>         <geogUnit>Countries</geogUnit>         <anlyUnit>Administrative units (geographical/political)</anlyUnit>         <universe>Cross-national;
